1. Creating Strings

A string is a sequence of characters enclosed in quotes.

let name = "Priya";
let city = 'Coimbatore';

console.log(name);
console.log(city);

Output:

Priya
Coimbatore
String Length

Use the .length property to find the number of characters.

let name = "Priya";

console.log(name.length);

Output:

5
Access Characters

Strings are indexed starting from 0.

P  r  i  y  a
0  1  2  3  4
let name = "Priya";

console.log(name[0]);
console.log(name[2]);

Output:

P
i
2. String Methods ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
toUpperCase()

Converts all letters to uppercase.

let name = "Priya";

console.log(name.toUpperCase());

Output:

PRIYA
toLowerCase()

Converts all letters to lowercase.

let name = "PRIYA";

console.log(name.toLowerCase());

Output:

priya
trim()

Removes spaces from the beginning and end.

let text = "   Hello JavaScript   ";

console.log(text.trim());

Output:

Hello JavaScript
concat()

Joins two or more strings.

let firstName = "Priya";
let lastName = "D";

console.log(firstName.concat(" ", lastName));

Output:

Priya D
replace()

Replaces the first matching text.

let message = "I like Java";

console.log(message.replace("Java", "JavaScript"));

Output:

I like JavaScript
replaceAll()

Replaces all matching text.

let text = "cat cat cat";

console.log(text.replaceAll("cat", "dog"));

Output:

dog dog dog
repeat()

Repeats a string.

console.log("Hi ".repeat(3));

Output:

Hi Hi Hi
3. Template Literals ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Template literals make it easy to insert variables into strings.

Instead of:

let name = "Priya";

console.log("Hello " + name);

Use:

let name = "Priya";

console.log(`Hello ${name}`);

Output:

Hello Priya
Multiple Variables
let name = "Priya";
let age = 27;

console.log(`My name is ${name} and I am ${age} years old.`);

Output:

My name is Priya and I am 27 years old.
Expressions
let a = 10;
let b = 20;

console.log(`Sum = ${a + b}`);

Output:

Sum = 30
4. String Searching ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
includes()

Checks if a string contains another string.

let text = "JavaScript";

console.log(text.includes("Script"));

Output:

true
startsWith()

Checks the beginning of a string.

let text = "JavaScript";

console.log(text.startsWith("Java"));

Output:

true
endsWith()

Checks the end of a string.

let text = "JavaScript";

console.log(text.endsWith("Script"));

Output:

true
indexOf()

Returns the position of the first occurrence.

let text = "JavaScript";

console.log(text.indexOf("S"));

Output:

4

If not found:

console.log(text.indexOf("Python"));

Output:

-1
lastIndexOf()

Returns the last occurrence.

let text = "apple apple";

console.log(text.lastIndexOf("apple"));

Output:

6
5. String Slicing ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
slice()

Extracts part of a string.

let text = "JavaScript";

console.log(text.slice(0, 4));

Output:

Java
substring()

Similar to slice().

let text = "JavaScript";

console.log(text.substring(4, 10));

Output:

Script
charAt()

Returns the character at a given index.

let text = "JavaScript";

console.log(text.charAt(2));

Output:

v
Real-World Examples
Capitalize a Name
let name = "priya";

let result =
    name.charAt(0).toUpperCase() +
    name.slice(1).toLowerCase();

console.log(result);

Output:

Priya
Check Email Domain
let email = "user@gmail.com";

if (email.endsWith("@gmail.com")) {
    console.log("Valid Gmail Address");
} else {
    console.log("Invalid Email");
}

Output:

Valid Gmail Address
Greeting Message
let name = "Priya";

console.log(`Welcome ${name}!`);

Output:

Welcome Priya!
Common Mistakes
❌ Forgetting Parentheses
let name = "Priya";

console.log(name.toUpperCase);

Output:

[Function: toUpperCase]
✅ Correct
console.log(name.toUpperCase());
❌ Using + Everywhere
let name = "Priya";
let age = 27;

console.log("Name: " + name + ", Age: " + age);
✅ Better
console.log(`Name: ${name}, Age: ${age}`);
Interview Questions ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
1. What is the difference between slice() and substring()?
slice() supports negative indexes.
substring() does not support negative indexes.

Example:

let text = "JavaScript";

console.log(text.slice(-6));      // Script
console.log(text.substring(-6));  // JavaScript
2. What does trim() do?

It removes whitespace from the beginning and end of a string.

3. What is a Template Literal?

A template literal is a string enclosed in backticks (`) that allows variable interpolation using ${}.

4. What is the difference between replace() and replaceAll()?
replace() replaces only the first match.
replaceAll() replaces every matching occurrence.
